                                                                                                        "replies": [
                                                                                                         {
                                                                                                          "content": "You raise an excellent point! I'm not actually certain that line 366 is where the timeout occurs - I was making an assumption based on the stack trace showing that line when the timeout happened. But you're absolutely right that this could just be where the code happened to be when the 10-second timeout expired.\n\nLooking at the stack trace more carefully:\n- The timeout occurs during `test_tokenize_basic` \n- The stack shows it's in `tokenize_source` at line 366 (`re.search`)\n- But this could just be coincidence - if there's an infinite loop elsewhere, the timeout might just catch it at whatever line is executing most frequently\n\nLet me reconsider the possibilities:\n\n1. **The test itself could have an issue** - maybe it's calling `tokenize_source` in a loop or with problematic input\n2. **There could be an infinite loop in the while loops** in `tokenize_source` (lines 333-343 or 365-375)\n3. **The regex might be fine** but something else is causing repeated execution\n\nLooking at the test:\n```python\ndef test_tokenize_basic():\n    source = '\\n    # Header comment\\n    x = \"string literal\"  # Inline comment\\n    y = 1\\n    '\n    tokenized, token_map = tokenize_source(source)\n    # ... assertions ...\n```\n\nThe test looks straightforward - just one call to `tokenize_source`. So the issue is likely within `tokenize_source` itself.\n\nThe most suspicious parts are the `while True:` loops that could become infinite if:\n- The regex keeps matching the same thing\n- The replacement doesn't actually change the string\n- The loop condition never becomes false\n\nI should investigate these while loops more carefully rather than focusing solely on the regex patterns.",
