                                                                                                                         {
                                                                                                                          "content": "I found the issue! The `create_token` function is returning a tuple `(token_name, hex_val)`, but the function signature says it returns a `str`. The `hex_val` being returned is `f\"'__TOKEN__{hex_content}__'\"` - notice it has quotes around it!\n\nThis means when we do the replacement at line 376:\n```python\nprocessed_line = processed_line[:match.start()] + hex_val + processed_line[match.end():]\n```\n\nWe're replacing `\"string literal\"` with `'__TOKEN__...__'` (with quotes). But then the regex pattern for strings will match this new string again because it has quotes! This creates an infinite loop where:\n\n1. Match `\"string literal\"`\n2. Replace with `'__TOKEN__...__'` (which is also a string with quotes)\n3. The regex matches `'__TOKEN__...__'` because it's a quoted string\n4. Check `contains_token('__TOKEN__...__')` which returns `True`\n5. Skip with `continue`\n6. But the regex will find the same match again on the next iteration!\n\nThe fix is to remove the quotes from the token so it's not recognized as a string by the regex:",
