                  "content": "I've successfully viewed the directory structure and read both the README.md and work_order.txt files. Here's a summary of what I found:\n\n**Directory Structure:**\nThe project is a Python library called \"bots\" that provides tools for working with Language Models (LLMs). It has a well-organized structure with:\n- Main library code in `bots/` directory\n- Tests in `tests/` directory\n- Examples and documentation\n- Various tools for code manipulation, including `python_edit.py`\n\n**README.md Summary:**\nThe bots library provides:\n- A unified interface for working with different LLM services (OpenAI, Anthropic)\n- Automatic function-to-tool conversion\n- Tree-based conversation management\n- Functional prompting patterns\n- Pre-built code tools\n- An auto terminal for interactive use\n- A lazy decorator for runtime code generation\n\n**Work Order Summary:**\nThe work_order.txt file describes the current implementation status of `python_edit.py`:\n- **Current Status**: 34 tests passing, 9 failing\n- **Completed**: Basic tokenization, comment handling, line insertion\n- **Remaining Issues**:\n  1. Scope-based insertion failing (e.g., `insert_after='OuterClass::another_method'`)\n  2. Source preservation tests failing (AST reconstruction not preserving formatting)\n  3. File-level operations not preserving structure correctly\n\nThe priority is to fix scope-based insertion next, as it's a distinct feature from line insertion.",
