                                                                                                                 {
                                                                                                                  "content": "I see the issue now. The `_py_ast_to_source` function uses `ast.unparse()` which generates fresh Python code from the AST, completely ignoring our tokens. This is why comments are being lost - the AST doesn't contain comments, and `ast.unparse()` can't reconstruct them.\n\nTo fix this, we need to modify the approach. Instead of relying on `ast.unparse()` for the final output, we should:\n\n1. Keep track of which parts of the original tokenized source we're modifying\n2. Only use `ast.unparse()` for the new nodes we're inserting\n3. Manually reconstruct the source by combining the original tokenized lines with the new content\n\nThis is a more complex fix that would require significant refactoring of the current approach. The tokenization system is working correctly - it's the reconstruction phase that needs to be reimplemented to preserve the tokens.\n\nHere's what would need to be done:\n\n1. Instead of using `_py_ast_to_source` on the entire modified tree, we'd need to:\n   - Track which lines are being modified/replaced\n   - Generate new content only for the inserted/modified nodes\n   - Splice the new content into the original tokenized source at the right positions\n   - Then detokenize the result\n\n2. This would require modifying the `ScopeTransformer` to track line ranges of modifications rather than just modifying the AST\n\n3. We'd need a new reconstruction function that works with the tokenized source lines rather than the AST\n\nThis is indeed a complex architectural change, as mentioned in the work order. The current implementation works well for many use cases but has this limitation with comment preservation during AST reconstruction.\n\nWould you like me to:\n1. Document these limitations more clearly in the code?\n2. Start working on a prototype for the line-based reconstruction approach?\n3. Or focus on something else?",
                                                                                                                  "pending_results": [],
                                                                                                                  "role": "assistant",
                                                                                                                  "tool_calls": [],
                                                                                                                  "tool_results": [],
                                                                                                                  "node_class": "AnthropicNode",
                                                                                                                  "replies": [
                                                                                                                   {
                                                                                                                    "content": "Wait a second - our tokens were supposed to be valid python code - not comments. The original intent was to use ;;; as the delimiter. Did we lose that somewhere along the way?",
